FROM maven:3.8.3-jdk-11 AS build
COPY src /home/app/src
COPY pom.xml /home/app
RUN mvn -f /home/app/pom.xml clean package

FROM openjdk:11.0.2-jdk-slim
COPY --from=build /home/app/target/builder-1.0.0.jar app.jar
ENV JAVA_OPTS=""
ADD src/main/resources/service_account_gcp.json service_account_gcp.json
ENV GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS "service_account_gcp.json"
ENTRYPOINT exec java $JAVA_OPTS  -jar /app.jar

✅ What Kind of Dockerfile Is This?
This is a **multi-stage Dockerfile** used for building and running a Java (Spring Boot / Maven) application.
Stage 1 (Builder stage): Uses Maven + JDK to compile the project and create a JAR file.
Stage 2 (Runtime stage): Uses a lightweight JDK image to run the JAR.

Multi-stage builds make the final Docker image smaller, faster, and more secure.
✅ Detailed Explanation of Each Step
Stage 1: Build Stage (Using Maven)
1. FROM maven:3.8.3-jdk-11 AS build
This sets the base image.
You are using the official Maven image (with Java 11).
AS build gives this stage a name so you can COPY from it later.

2. COPY src /home/app/src
Copies your project’s source code (src folder) from your system into the container at /home/app/src.

3. COPY pom.xml /home/app
Copies the pom.xml file to the container.
Maven needs pom.xml to download dependencies and build the application.

4. RUN mvn -f /home/app/pom.xml clean package
Runs Maven inside the container:
clean removes old build files
package compiles the code and creates the JAR file under /home/app/target/...jar.
This will generate something like:
/home/app/target/jello-builder-1.0.0.jar

✔ By doing this inside the container, you do NOT need Maven installed on your laptop.

Stage 2: Runtime Stage (Using Lightweight JDK)
5. FROM openjdk:11.0.2-jdk-slim
Starts the second stage.
Uses a slim (lightweight) Java image to run the JAR file.
This makes the final image very small.

6. COPY --from=build /home/app/target/jello-builder-1.0.0.jar app.jar
Copies the built JAR from the first stage (build) into the second stage.
The JAR is renamed to app.jar.

7. ENV JAVA_OPTS=""
Sets an environment variable.
JAVA_OPTS is used to pass custom JVM options at runtime.
Example:
-Xms512m -Xmx1024m

Currently, it's empty.

8. ADD src/main/resources/service_account_gcp.json service_account_gcp.json
Adds the GCP service account JSON file to the container.
This is usually used for:
Pub/Sub
BigQuery
Cloud Storage
Cloud SQL Auth
⚠ But copying credentials into the image is generally unsafe.
Better: mount as a Kubernetes secret.

9. ENV GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS "service_account_gcp.json"
Sets GCP credential environment variable.
Google SDKs automatically use this path to authenticate.

10. ENTRYPOINT exec java $JAVA_OPTS -jar /app.jar
This is the command that starts your application when the container runs.
exec ensures proper signal handling (useful for Kubernetes).
java $JAVA_OPTS -jar /app.jar runs the Spring Boot app.
Example if you set JAVA_OPTS:
docker run -e JAVA_OPTS="-Xmx1024m" appimage

✅ Summary Table
Line	Meaning
FROM maven… AS build	Use Maven to build the app
COPY src	Copy source code
COPY pom.xml	Copy pom.xml
RUN mvn clean package	Build JAR
FROM openjdk slim	Lightweight runtime environment
COPY --from=build	Copy JAR from builder stage
ENV JAVA_OPTS	Optional Java settings
ADD GCP key file	Add credentials
ENV GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS	Set Google auth location
ENTRYPOINT java -jar	Start application
